{"pageProps":{"tutorial":{"title":"CSS Flexbox","slug":"css-flexbox","subject":"CSS","category":"Web Development","level":"Advanced","estimated_read_time":"25 mins","prerequisites":["CSS Display Property","CSS Box Model"],"learning_objectives":["Understand Flex Container vs Flex Item","flex-direction","justify-content","align-items","flex-wrap","flex-grow, flex-shrink, flex-basis"],"theory":"The Flexible Box Layout Module (Flexbox) makes it easier to design flexible responsive layout structure without using float or positioning.\n\n*   `display: flex`: Activates flexbox on the parent.\n*   `flex-direction`: row, column, row-reverse, column-reverse.\n*   `justify-content`: Aligns items horizontally (main axis).\n*   `align-items`: Aligns items vertically (cross axis).","syntax":".container {\n  display: flex;\n  justify-content: center;\n  align-items: center;\n}","examples":[{"code":"/* Perfect Centering */\n.center {\n  display: flex;\n  justify-content: center;\n  align-items: center;\n  height: 100vh;\n}","output":"The child element is perfectly centered horizontally and vertically.","explanation":"The holy grail of CSS layout, solved by Flexbox."}],"common_mistakes":[{"mistake":"Using justify-content on column direction","correction":"When `flex-direction: column`, the main axis rotates. `justify-content` now controls vertical alignment.","example":""}],"interview_questions":[{"question":"What is the difference between `align-items` and `align-content`?","answer":"`align-items` aligns items in a single line. `align-content` aligns lines in a multi-line flex container.","difficulty":"Hard"}],"practice_problems":[{"problem":"Create a row of 3 items spread apart evenly.","hint":"justify-content","solution":"justify-content: space-between;","difficulty":"Easy"}],"real_world_use_cases":[{"scenario":"Navigation Bars","description":"Flexbox is perfect for Navbars: Logo on far left, links in center, login button on far right.","code":".nav { display: flex; justify-conte